    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix buffer overflow vulnerability in rfsimu_setchanmod_cmd function\n\n### Summary\nThe `rfsimu_setchanmod_cmd` function in the RF simulator contained a buffer overflow vulnerability due to improper handling of memory allocated by `sscanf` with the `%m` specifier. The function was calling `free()` on potentially uninitialized pointers when `sscanf` failed to allocate memory, leading to undefined behavior and potential crashes.\n\nThis issue occurred when the telnet command parser processed malformed input strings for setting channel models. Under certain conditions with invalid input, the function would attempt to free memory that was never allocated, causing segmentation faults.\n\n### Changes\n- `radio/rfsimulator/simulator.cpp`: Added NULL pointer checks before calling `free()` on `modelname` and `modeltype` pointers allocated by `sscanf` with `%m` specifier.\n\nThe fix ensures that `free()` is only called on pointers that were successfully allocated by `sscanf`, preventing crashes when the function receives malformed input or when memory allocation fails.\n\n### Reproduction\nThe issue can be reproduced by sending a malformed \"setmodel\" command through the telnet interface to the RF simulator with insufficient or malformed parameters. This causes the `sscanf` call to fail to allocate memory for one or both of the string parameters, leaving the pointers in an undefined state. When the function then attempts to free these pointers, it results in undefined behavior and potential segmentation fault.\n"
}